Multi Level and Quantile Models in BRMS

A notebook which is testing the implementation of BRMS quantile hierarchical models using generated datasets.

No Relationship

First lets generate some data where there is absolutely no relationship to it at all. We will fit a normal linear model.

\[ y_i\;{\sim}\;\mathcal{N}(\mu_i, \sigma_i) \] In this instance, we will assume no relationshi

We will then fit some quantile models. In the quantile bayesian quantile regression, we fit an asymmetric Laplace distribution:

\[ y_i\;=\;Laplace(m_i, \lambda_i,p_i) \] \(m\) is a location parameter, \(\lamda\) is a scale parameter, and \(p\) is a quantile/percentile parameter, representing the quantile of interest. When used for Bayesian inference, the asymmetric laplace funtion displays the same properties as the loss function used in quantile regression. \[ \displaystyle f(x;m,\lambda ,p)={\frac {p(1-p)}{\lambda }}{\begin{cases}\exp \left(-((p-1)/\lambda )(x-m)\right)&{\text{if }}x\leq m\\[4pt]\exp(-(p/\lambda )(x-m))&{\text{if }}x>m\end{cases}} \]

We will visualise the results and see how they compare.


library(ggplot2)
library(ggExtra)
library(brms)
library(bayesplot)
library(tidybayes)
library(magrittr)
library(tidyr)
library(dplyr)

number_of_samples <- 500

# Generating random points
# Using skew normal distribution, but skewness is 0
X <- brms::rskew_normal(n=number_of_samples,mu = 10,sigma = 1,alpha = 0)
y <- brms::rskew_normal(n=number_of_samples,mu = 2,sigma = 2,alpha = 0)

df <- tibble::as_tibble(list(
  x=X,
  y=y
))



plot <- ggplot(df, aes(x,y))+
  geom_point()

plot <- ggMarginal(plot,type="histogram")
plot


m <- brms::brm(y~x,data = df)

m_q0.75 <- brms::brm(bf(y~x, 
                        quantile=0.75),
                     data=df,
                     family=asym_laplace())




number_of_samples <- 500



# Generating random points
# Using skew normal distribution, but skewness is 0
X <- brms::rskew_normal(n=number_of_samples,mu = 10,sigma = 1,alpha = 0)
y <- brms::rskew_normal(n=number_of_samples,mu = 2,sigma = 2,alpha = 0)

df <- tibble::as_tibble(list(
  x=X,
  y=y
))



plot <- ggplot(df, aes(x,y))+
  geom_point()

plot <- ggMarginal(plot,type="histogram")
plot
